<p>This is a my function </p>  <pre><code>st3 = (x, y) -&gt;   console.log "#{x?}, #{y?}"   if [x?, y?] is [true, true]   # &lt;- this is the line     'good'   'bad' </code></pre>  <p>This is the output</p>  <pre><code>true, true bad </code></pre>  <p>I want to be able to do a tuple comparison like it is in python.</p>  <p>In python, the <code>if</code> can be written roughly as</p>  <pre><code> if (x, y) == (True, False):    return 'good' </code></pre>  <p>The coffescript <code>if</code> loop is translated into javascript as such</p>  <pre><code>if ([x != null, y != null] === [true, true]) {   'good'; } </code></pre>  <p>That's why this will not evaluated to true.</p>  <p>Is there any alternative way to express it in coffeescript?</p>